Sed

There will come moments when we want to change specific names in the whole file or standard input. One of the tools we can use for this is the stream editor called sed. One of the most common uses of this is substituting text. Here, sed looks for patterns we have defined in the form of regular expressions (regex) and replaces them with another pattern that we have also defined. Let us stick to the last results and say we want to replace the word "bin" with "BOX."

The "s" flag at the beginning stands for the substitute command. Then we specify the pattern we want to replace. After the slash (/), we enter the pattern we want to use as a replacement in the third position. Finally, we use the "g" flag, which stands for replacing all matches.

